<IFRAME FRAMEBORDER=1 ALIGN=CENTER width=100% HEIGHT=200 SCROLLING=YES SRC="http://boards.stratics.com/forums/Forum71/HTML/000725.html">
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width="95%"><TR><td bgcolor="#400000"><TABLE BORDER=0 cellpadding=4 border=0 cellspacing=1 WIDTH="100%"><TR bgcolor="#400000"><TD COLSPAN=2><CENTER><FONT SIZE="2" COLOR="#FFFFFF" FACE="Comic Sans MS, Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, MS Sans">T O P I C  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; R E V I E W</font></CENTER></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Comic Sans MS, Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, MS Sans">Ninvaen</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Comic Sans MS, Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, MS Sans">Hello!<P>I can't even decide what "class" I'd like to play.  Currently I'm leaning toward a War Mage or an Archer.<P>The War mage appeals because at level 1 I was blowing things away before they could reach me.  I also have a very nice Roleplay set up for this character.  This type of character might be too common for my liking though...is it?<P>The Archer appeals because it sounds less popular, while at the same time sounds cool.  Flaming arrows and all...  But I've heard much complaining about this "class".  Not even comparable with melee and magic I understand...<P>So, which one is more/less common?  Are they both strong or is one more strong than the other?  Which one is more fun?  Which would you want/respect more; high level war mage or archer?<P>Thanks for any information/opinions you can offer this newbie!  I appreciate your time =D</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Comic Sans MS, Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, MS Sans">Gelum Fyre</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Comic Sans MS, Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, MS Sans">As far as role playing, as a non-magic using character, I have great respect for the mages.  I am wary of magics and feel that giving them proper respect keeps me on the right side (rather than on the receiving end of the magic).  I am not PK, so it doesn't REALLY matter.<P>I think archery is great, but I respect the seasoned swordsman over archers (in general).  That's just me.<P>Someone honorable deserves respect regardless of "class".</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Comic Sans MS, Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, MS Sans">JerryF</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Comic Sans MS, Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, MS Sans">Well if you want to kill a LOT of lower level creatures EASIER, try a War Mage first.  I have experimented with one and at level ONE I was able to kill any 2,3, or 4th level creature with ease (just blast them at a safe distance).  My main character who's kind of a hybrid warrior and life magic (cleric type) is level 4 and still has a HARD time killing the Level 4 Drudge Slinker/Sneaker classes (he can do it but almost always has to heal or wait for HP to go up after the fight).  I don't know if this obvious advantage to the warmage character lasts longer into the game (I encountered a skeleton in the desert last night that ran so fast he was upon me before I got the 2nd spell off), but early on they are devistating.<P>I also have a "newbie question".  As for Spell components, how long do they last?  I was able to cast at LEAST 100 fire1 spells with the SAME 5 components.  In UO, the reagents lasted ONE try only.  Is this just a beta thing, or will they be a one-shot-deal later on?</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Comic Sans MS, Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, MS Sans">Korinarr</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Comic Sans MS, Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, MS Sans">Sometimes the components burn, sometimes they don't. Carry spares.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Comic Sans MS, Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, MS Sans">Sterling</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Comic Sans MS, Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, MS Sans">However, they're inexpensive and fairly easy to get.  Carry at least 5 at a time, and you should be fine.</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE></td></tr></table> 
</IFRAME>
</FONT>
